WEBVTT

00:03.592 --> 00:12.422
It was a dissertation by a fellow who had passed 
away, and his wife had sent it to us and asked us if we

00:03.592 --> 00:12.422
were interested in publishing it. He had worked 
with the Corps of Engineers for many years, and it

00:14.004 --> 00:31.405
was on the subject of the

00:14.004 --> 00:31.405
development of the mouth of the Mississippi 
River, the channelization of the Mississippi,

00:31.823 --> 00:44.102
and opening it up to heavy ship traffic. And that 
was the dissertation, but it was absolutely, it

00:44.122 --> 00:51.914
was like reading a finished book. It wasn't like a 
dissertation at all. It didn't have the usual

00:54.238 --> 01:00.227
dissertation ease and the view of literature and 
notes to every phrase, extremely well written,

01:00.916 --> 01:07.444
and I wanted to publish that. And I was in the middle 
of negotiations with the man's wife and had told

01:07.865 --> 01:14.994
her that we would like to publish it. And she wrote 
to me and said that the Corps of Engineers had

01:15.694 --> 01:23.424
gotten in touch with her and they wanted to publish 
it. And so they did. We missed out on that. I think

01:26.638 --> 01:43.081
that would have been a really good book, and I think 
it would have led us into doing some stuff in

01:26.638 --> 01:43.081
history of technology and southern history, too, 
that we didn't get into until much more recently.

01:45.163 --> 01:51.392
How does an editor attract manuscripts?

01:51.963 --> 01:54.566
You attract manuscripts by publishing good 
books. You find manuscripts by getting out there

01:54.666 --> 02:13.007
and talking to people, going to meetings, talking 
to people on the phone, just talking to people

01:54.666 --> 02:13.007
about their students and who's doing good work and 
about their colleagues and finding out who's got

01:54.666 --> 02:13.007
the manuscripts. And then you make the contact 
with them and ask them if they haven't written a

02:20.870 --> 02:23.734
manuscript yet, if they would consider writing 
one. If they do have the manuscript, have they

02:23.835 --> 02:27.220
presented it to someone else? And if not, could you 
see a proposal on it? Give an example of one that you

02:30.925 --> 02:38.317
recall where that worked, where you did that. Oh, 
that's the standard practice. Practically every

02:42.603 --> 02:48.953
manuscript we get is now something that we either 
have attracted through our previous

02:49.540 --> 03:09.046
publications or that we've gone out and

02:49.540 --> 03:09.046
contacted the author and asked that the author let 
us have a look at it. I do that pretty often in the

03:09.687 --> 03:14.032
Eastern European series. Stepan Nestrovich is 
the series editor, and he and I often contact

03:19.072 --> 03:30.146
people whose work we've heard about and ask them if 
they will

03:19.072 --> 03:30.146
provide us with the prospectus. I've just begun

03:31.348 --> 03:38.978
what we call the Centennial of Flight series. And 
Roger Lanius, the chief historian at NASA, is the

03:40.180 --> 03:46.107
general editor of that series. And he and I have 
actually asked people to contribute books to the

03:48.620 --> 03:53.244
series. And these are people who have done other 
writing in the history of aviation and

03:53.444 --> 03:58.269
aeronautics. And so we don't even have a 
manuscript on that in that series yet, but we have

03:59.470 --> 04:06.116
15 books lined up for it. Everything from the 
man's, humanity's visions and imaginations

04:06.857 --> 04:18.407
about flight long before flight was possible, 
through the light or the air period into the early

04:19.130 --> 04:25.822
years of aviation and right on up to the space age. 
And I'm hoping that whoever takes my place here

04:26.563 --> 04:34.157
will continue that series and working with Roger. 
And maybe there'll be 20 or 25 books in the series

04:34.237 --> 04:42.792
before it's really closed out in about 2004 or 5. 
But we have about 15 titles lined up for it now.

